\subsection{Single-Column Model Verification and Observation Comparison}
\label{subsec:numerical_verification}

We verify the prognostic 4D GSPT SBL formulation by comparing SCM (Single-Column Model) simulations against observational data from three highly contrasting field campaigns: the Cooperative Atmosphere-Surface Exchange Study 1999 (\textbf{CASES99}), the Fluxes Over Snow Surfaces (\textbf{FLOSS}) experiment, and the Surface Heat Budget of the Arctic Ocean (\textbf{SHEBA}) campaign.

\paragraph{Physical Setup and Surface Drag Forcing.}
The primary physical differences between these environments lie in their surface boundary structures and thermal insulation profiles. Our numerical simulations initialize these setups under clear nocturnal radiative cooling conditions, varying the local aerodynamic roughness length $z_{0m}$ and the skin layer thermal capacity $C_{\mathrm{skin}}$:
\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{CASES99 (Grassland Plains):} Featuring a moderate roughness length ($z_{0m} \approx 0.02\,\mathrm{m}$), the heterogeneous canopy exerts a strong frictional torque on the surface wind field. This high-drag regime acts as a continuous source of mechanical shear, which physically expands the active critical manifold sheet $\mathcal{M}_0^{\text{act}}$ and anchors the boundary layer in a weakly turbulent, coupled state under low geostrophic wind speeds.
    \item \textbf{FLOSS (Fluxes Over Snow Surfaces):} Smooth snow cover features an exceptionally low roughness length ($z_{0m} \approx 1.0 \times 10^{-4}\,\mathrm{m}$), which severely suppresses mechanical shear production. Furthermore, the high thermal insulation of the snowpack isolates the skin layer from geothermal soil heat flux, accelerating radiative cooling. This rapid cooling shifts the linear active manifold sheet downward along the TKE axis. Consequently, the FLOSS regime requires much higher geostrophic winds ($U_g > 8\,\mathrm{m\,s}^{-1}$) to sustain active mixing; under weaker forcing, the system undergoes a rapid, complete turbulent collapse.
    \item \textbf{SHEBA (Arctic Pack Ice):} The perennial sea ice pack presents an extreme aerodynamic environment ($z_{0m} \approx 1.0 \times 10^{-4}\,\mathrm{m}$) coupled with high seasonal variation in radiative forcing. To capture the deep vertical shear profiles observed across the ice sheet, the model incorporates an expanded master length scale ($l_0 = 15.0\,\mathrm{m}$) and an adjusted shear efficiency parameter ($\eta = 1.5$), stabilizing the boundary layer against immediate collapse during prolonged polar nights.
\end{itemize}

